      <prompt>
        <p>A 24-year-old known diabetic has had diarrhoea and vomiting prior to attending hospital. On arrival he reports polyuria, his blood glucose reading is 30 mmol/l (normal 3.3–5.5 mmol/l) and urine dipstick is positive for ketones. His arterial blood gas has the following results:</p>
        <p>pH: 7.12 (normal pH 7.35-7.43)</p>
        <p>
          <i>Pa</i>
          O
          <sub>2</sub>
          : 12.5 kPa (normal range 12–15 kPa)
        </p>
        <p>
          <i>Pa</i>
          CO
          <sub>2</sub>
          : 3.0 kPa (normal range 4.5–6.0 kPa)
        </p>
        <p>Bicarbonate: 12 mmol/l (normal range 22–29 mmol/l)</p>
        <p>Base excess: –15 mmol/l (normal range –3 to +3 mmol/l)</p>
        <p>Which of the following is the correct diagnosis?</p>
      </prompt>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_000">Metabolic acidosis</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_001">Metabolic alkalosis</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_002">Normal arterial blood gas</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_003">Respiratory acidosis</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_004">Respiratory alkalosis</simpleChoice>
    </choiceInteraction>
  </itemBody>
  <modalFeedback identifier="CORRECT_FEEDBACK" outcomeIdentifier="GENERAL_FEEDBACK" showHide="show">
    <p>
      <b>Option A is Correct.</b>
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Option B is Incorrect.</b>
      This causes a high pH and high bicarbonate.
